BEGIN_TEXT
Question 37:
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
Let \( f(x) = kx^2 + B \) and \( g(x)=C^{2x} \) and 
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \  h(x)=kx^{2}C^{2x}+BC^{2x}+C^{2x} \) .
$BR $SPACE $BR  
Suppose \( f($x)= $f \) and  \( g($x)= $g \) . 
$BR $SPACE $BR
Evaluate  \( h($x) = \) \{ ans_rule(10) \} (your answer should be a number) 
$BR 
END_TEXT

ANS( num_cmp( $ans ));

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
In order to evaluate \( h($x) \), we need to express the formula for \( h(x) \)
in terms of \( f(x) \) and \( g(x) \). Factoring gives \( h(x)=C^{2x}(kx^{2}+B+1)\).
$BR $SPACE $BR 
Since \( g(x)=C^{2x} \) and \( f(x)=kx^2+B \), we can re-write the formula for
\( h(x) \) as \( h(x)=g(x)\cdot (f(x)+1) \). Thus,
$BR $SPACE $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ h($x) = g($x)\cdot (f($x)+1) \)
$BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ = $g ($f+1) \)
$BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ = $ans \).
$BR
END_SOLUTION



